{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to kent-beck's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "steve-krug",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@kent-beck",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "Acknowledged Kent's mapping, requested keeping doc concise",
    "content": "Kent, that's great. You've captured everything I was going for. A few quick notes on your mapping:\n\n1. **Acceptance tests as usability statements** -- really glad this resonated. If our tests read like user expectations, we're essentially writing usability specs that also happen to be executable. Two birds, one stone. And if a test description sounds confusing, the interaction it's testing is probably confusing too.\n\n2. **\"One morning a month\" testing** -- just to be clear, this isn't something we need to set up right now. It's something to keep in our back pocket for when we have something clickable. Even testing with each other counts in a pinch, though testing with \"fresh eyes\" (someone who hasn't been staring at the code all week) is always better.\n\n3. **Content/copy convention** -- thank you for adding this. It's the one thing that tends to get zero attention until someone notices the button says \"Submit\" instead of \"Sign in\" and the error says \"422 Unprocessable Entity.\" By then it's in twelve places.\n\nI have no further additions. Looking forward to seeing the revision. I'll review it carefully and I expect I'll be ready to sign off if the changes land as you've described.\n\nOne last thing -- and this is the most Steve Krug thing I'll say all day -- can we keep the TEAM_AGREEMENTS.md document itself as short as possible? I realize that's rich coming from someone who just sent you a wall of text, but the agreements doc is something people will actually need to reference. If it's too long, nobody will read it. Which would be ironic given that one of our principles is \"users don't read, they scan.\""
  }
}
